ost significantly, from growing things to selling them exemplified the enormous social effort required to domesticate the profit motive and turn it into the practical foundation of civic life. As Zakim reveals in his highly original study, there was nothing natural or preordained about the stunning ascendance of this capitalism and its radical transformation of the relationship between “Man and Mammon.”  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCapitalismxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aCapitalism-Social aspects-United States-History-19th century. 0aClerkszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aClerks-United States-History-19th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aaccounting.  acapitalism.  aindividualism.  aknowledge.  amarket economy.  amasculinity.  anervous disorders.  aoffice work.  apaperwork.  astatistics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226545899423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226545899/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles